## Nested Types (Member Types)

C++ lets you define types -- classes, structs, enums, and type aliases -- inside another class. These are called **nested types** or **member types**. They belong to the enclosing class's scope, so you access them through the class name using the scope resolution operator `::`.

### Why use nested types?

- Keeps a helper type co-located with the class that owns it, reducing namespace clutter.
- Signals to readers that the type is tightly coupled to the outer class and should not be used independently.
- Prevents name collisions with other types in the same namespace.

### Nested enums

The most common use case. Instead of a free-standing `enum class Direction` polluting a namespace, place it inside the class that needs it:

```cpp
class Sprite {
public:
    enum class Direction { Up, Down, Left, Right };

    void move(Direction d);

private:
    Direction m_facing { Direction::Down };
};

// Caller:
Sprite s{};
s.move(Sprite::Direction::Right);
```

Outside the class, callers write `Sprite::Direction::Right`. Inside member functions, the `Sprite::` prefix is not needed.

### Nested classes and structs

A class can contain a full class definition. Since C++11, a nested class is implicitly considered a friend of the enclosing class, meaning it has access to the enclosing class's private and protected members. The outer class can also access all members of the nested class.

### Nested type aliases (`using`)

A common pattern is to expose an implementation detail through a cleaner alias:

```cpp
class Buffer {
public:
    using value_type = unsigned char;
    using size_type  = std::size_t;
};
```

This mirrors how the standard library exposes `Container::value_type`, and it allows generic code to introspect the class without knowing its internals.

### Access control

Nested types obey the same `public`/`private`/`protected` rules as member variables. A `private` nested type is only visible inside the enclosing class and its friends. A `public` nested type is visible to all callers.

### Relationship to prior lessons

Because nested types belong to the class's scope, they interact naturally with member functions introduced in *The hidden `this` pointer and member function chaining* -- member functions can name nested types without any prefix. When splitting a class across a header and an implementation file (see *Classes and header files*), nested type declarations stay in the header inside the class body; only the definitions of member functions move to the `.cpp` file.

