## Class Templates with Member Functions

A **class template** lets you write a single class definition that works for many types. The compiler generates a concrete class -- a **template instantiation** -- each time you use the template with a specific type argument.

### Defining a class template

Prefix the class with `template <typename T>`. Every member function defined outside the class body must repeat the template parameter list and use the full `ClassName<T>::` qualifier.

```cpp
#include <iostream>

template <typename T>
class Pair {
public:
    T first{}, second{};
    Pair(T a, T b) : first{a}, second{b} {}
    T max() const { return first > second ? first : second; }
};

int main() {
    Pair<int>    pi{3, 7};
    Pair<double> pd{1.5, 0.9};
    std::cout << pi.max() << '\n';   // 7
    std::cout << pd.max() << '\n';   // 1.5
}
```

### Member functions defined outside the class body

When you split declaration and definition, each out-of-class member function needs its own `template <typename T>` header:

```cpp
template <typename T>
T Pair<T>::max() const { return first > second ? first : second; }
```

This is the same reason covered in *Classes and header files*: if the definition lives in a `.cpp` file the compiler won't see it when instantiating the template for another translation unit. Keep template definitions in headers (or in an `.inl` file included at the bottom of the header).

### Template instantiation

The compiler only generates code for member functions that are actually called. `Pair<int>` and `Pair<double>` are completely independent types -- there is no implicit conversion between them.

### Multiple template parameters

A template can have more than one type parameter:

```cpp
template <typename T, typename U>
class Pair { T first{}; U second{}; /* ... */ };
```

This lets first and second hold different types, which a single-parameter `Pair<T>` cannot express.

### What types work?

Any type `T` that satisfies the operations used in the member functions. If `max()` uses `operator>`, then `T` must provide it. In C++20 you can make this requirement explicit with **concepts**, but that is covered separately.

### Connection to prior lessons

The `this` pointer (see *The hidden this pointer and member function chaining*) works exactly the same inside template member functions -- `this` is just `Pair<T>*`. Destructors (see *Introduction to destructors*) are also templated: `~Pair()` inside a `Pair<T>` definition is implicitly `~Pair<T>()`.

