## Ref qualifiers

Ref qualifiers let you overload a member function based on whether the object it is called on is an lvalue or an rvalue. They work the same way `const` qualifiers work, except they control *value category* rather than mutability.

You append `&` or `&&` after the parameter list (and after `const`, if present) to restrict or distinguish the call:

- `void f() &` -- callable only on lvalue objects
- `void f() &&` -- callable only on rvalue objects
- Providing both overloads lets the compiler pick the right one automatically

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

struct Buffer {
    std::string data;

    // Safe to return a reference when *this is an lvalue
    const std::string& get() const & { return data; }

    // Move the data out when *this is a temporary
    std::string get() && { return std::move(data); }
};

Buffer make() { return Buffer{"hello"}; }

int main() {
    Buffer b{"world"};
    std::cout << b.get() << '\n';       // calls const &
    std::cout << make().get() << '\n';  // calls &&
}
```

### Why this matters

Without ref qualifiers, a member returning `const T&` on a temporary is dangerous: the caller may bind the returned reference to a local variable and the temporary will be destroyed before the reference is used. The `&&` overload sidesteps this by moving the value out instead.

This concept connects to the resource-ownership ideas discussed in **Introduction to destructors**. Ref qualifiers are how the standard library implements methods like `std::optional::value()`, which behaves differently when the optional is a temporary.

### Key rules

- You cannot mix ref-qualified and unqualified overloads of the same function -- all overloads must be qualified or none of them.
- `const &` matches both `const` lvalues and, as a fallback, rvalues (when no `&&` overload is present).
- Ref qualifiers apply to `*this`, not to the function parameters.
- They have no runtime cost -- selection is entirely at compile time.

