## Chapter 15 Summary: More on Classes

This chapter covered a set of class features that together give you precise control over object lifetime, access, sharing, and interface design.

**The hidden `this` pointer and method chaining**
Every non-static member function receives an implicit `this` pointer to the calling object. Returning `*this` by reference from a member function enables method chaining -- calling multiple member functions on the same object in one expression.

**Classes and header files**
Class definitions go in `.h` files; member function definitions go in `.cpp` files. Inline definitions inside the class body are implicitly `inline`. This separation keeps compile times manageable and lets multiple translation units share the same class definition.

**Nested types (member types)**
A type declared inside a class is scoped to that class (`MyClass::NestedEnum`). Use nested types when the type is only meaningful in the context of the enclosing class and you want to avoid polluting the enclosing namespace.

**Destructors**
A destructor (`~ClassName()`) runs automatically when an object goes out of scope or is deleted. It takes no parameters and has no return type. Use it to release resources: close file handles, free heap memory, or decrement reference counts. RAII depends on destructors running reliably.

**Class templates with member functions**
Member function definitions for a class template must repeat the template parameter list. The compiler instantiates a separate version for each type used. Keep template definitions in headers so the compiler can see them at the point of use.

**Static member variables and functions**
A `static` data member belongs to the class, not to any instance. It must be defined exactly once outside the class body (unless `inline` or `constexpr`). A `static` member function has no `this` pointer and can only access static members directly.

**Friend non-member functions and friend classes**
`friend` grants a specific function or class access to private and protected members. Friendship is neither inherited nor transitive. Prefer non-member friend functions (e.g., `operator<<`) over friend classes when possible, to minimise the size of the trust boundary.

**Friend member functions**
A specific member function of another class can be made a friend. Forward declarations are often needed to resolve ordering dependencies between the two class definitions.

**Ref qualifiers**
Appending `&` or `&&` to a member function signature restricts it to lvalue or rvalue objects respectively. Use ref qualifiers to prevent operations (like chaining assignment) from silently binding to temporaries.

**Combined example -- static counter + destructor + chaining:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
struct Widget {
    inline static int s_count{0};
    int m_val;
    explicit Widget(int v) : m_val{v} { ++s_count; }
    ~Widget() { --s_count; }
    Widget& set(int v) & { m_val = v; return *this; }
    Widget& add(int v) & { m_val += v; return *this; }
    static int count() { return s_count; }
};
int main() {
    Widget w{1};
    w.set(10).add(5);  // chaining
    std::cout << w.m_val << ' ' << Widget::count() << '\n'; // 15 1
}
```

